GoodReads Review of Thrawn: Alliances (Star Wars: Thrawn, #2): Rating - 3/5
reviews.content:
I'm a big fan of Zahn's work in general and his Star Wars books have always been great. Thrawn: Alliances, which marks the second Thrawn novel in the rebooted Star Wars post-Disney universe is a good book. Like Zahn's other works it stands out as being way better than the majority of Star Wars novels. But this is also the worst of them. That doesn't make it bad, I still enjoyed it, but it just doesn't stand up to his previous books, even the last Thrawn novel.

I don't like Episodes 1-3. I'll put that up front. Clone Wars (the animated series x2) was fine. Rebels is ok. I don't have an irrational hatred for Anakin Skywalker as a character beyond the fact that it's very hard to separate portrayals of him as a hero from the fact that he goes on to just... murder a ton of children. But whatever, that wasn't what bothered me. He just was an irritating character in this novel, in about half of which he unexpectedly stars.

Perhaps this impression was compounded by the fact that I listened to the audiobook, which is usually great for Star Wars novels. I do not recommend the experience this time. The narrator does the voices of Anakin and Padme spot on from Episode 2, which means half the book is listening to whiny teen voices. Like it made me want to dive into the book and strangle both characters. It wasn't distracting, because it was spot on from the films, it was just those characters and you were unable to forget that they Like Totally Sounded Like That in the movies and it was the worst.

But then on top of that, the characters are exactly like they were in Episode 2, boringly self-interested, overly fraught, acting with little care to the consequences of their actions. I get it... those were the characters... but they were bad characters in the film and Zahn manages to capture their terribleness completely accurately... which just isn't great.

Honestly, it was all a little unnecessary. The historical bits didn't feel like they served much of a purpose except to maybe try and patch up some plot holes in the larger universe? It wasn't a particularly interesting B story, precisely because we know exactly what's going to happen to all these characters now and there are no stakes. The 'modern' portions with Vader and Thrawn playing off each other were far more interesting. The tactics are interesting. Trying to track what Thrawn is thinking is interesting. All of it was interesting. That said, even there it didn't quite rise to the level of his previous works. If you like Star Wars or Thrawn, pick this up I guess (but not the audiobook). But don't expect Heir to the Empire, because this ain't that.

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of The Definitive Irredeemable Vol. 1: Rating - 5/5
reviews.content:
Mark Waid's Irredeemable is, perhaps, the comic-reader's comic book. Someone with no experience of the comic book world could pick up the series and enjoy it greatly. However, they wouldn't get the full experience of Waid's effort without some knowledge of the superhero genre.

If you know anything of Waid's previous work (say, Kingdom Come), you know that he delights in taking heroes to the end of their rope. Irredeemable is no different. It is a book about heroes and their humanity, or lack of.

It's impossible to properly tell you about the dark masterpiece that is this narrative without ruining it. Just understand that Waid will take the superhero story and dissect it in a way that few others have succeed in doing.

Read it all the way to the end. The conclusion to the story (not in this volume, but available in smaller collections) is one of the most satisfying I've ever read.

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of Storykiller: Rating - 3/5
reviews.content:
An artifact of the internet's strange and incredibly strong preference for plot over form. Storykiller, like many self-started, self-published, internet-fan-supported novels, displays strong plotting that lays out a good narrative with good drive behind it.

However, the characters are somewhat weak, though they improve by the end of the novel, and the writing style leaves something to be desired. While the plot has clearly been thought out, the mechanics of the writing are still rough. Especially in a few places where the story becomes disjointed, like a record skipping a beat, before it all comes back together.

All said, there's still plenty in the novel to recommend to a reader, especially the fan of meta-fiction or of Buffy and her monster-of-the-week ilk, who are clear progenitors of Storykiller's protagonist.

books.author: Stuart Kelly

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of The Book of Lost Books: An Incomplete History of All the Great Books You'll Never Read: Rating - 5/5
GoodReads Review of Mr. Penumbra's 24-Hour Bookstore (Mr. Penumbra's 24-Hour Bookstore, #1): Rating - 4/5
reviews.content:
Reading this book was a weird experience. Highly enjoyable, but strange.

The weird part is just how specifically the book feels aimed at my interests. I honestly didn't think that there were many other geeks with the specific combination of love for design, marketing, books (printed and electronic), fonts, code, Google and general hackery, but there must be, because this book is steeped in all of those topics and more, bringing them together in one wonderful mystery and then unwrapping it all before our eyes.

The book is solid, well written and fun. The only major flaw is that the pacing occasionally gets bogged down as Sloan goes deeper with her characters. The characters are all interesting, though (with the exception of the protagonist) they tend to be there as representatives of single specific geeky interests. As a result, the tangents are neither bad nor uninteresting, it just means that the flow can be inconsistent.

All that being said, it's absolute love with every subject it touches upon more than makes up for its flaws. A great read. If you're interests are anywhere close to the ones in the list above, pick it up.

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of Running with the Demon (Word & Void, #1): Rating - 5/5
reviews.content:
Terry Brooks' Running with Demon is the prototypical urban fantasy novel. Published in 1997, it is one of the earliest novels to approach the genre and gain widespread readership.

Running with the Demon introduces Brooks' world of the Word and the Void, opposing forces of chaos and order that set the stage for a well-developed unique moral relativity that serves as the bedrock of a unique narrative.

The book features excellent characters, a unique and interesting approach to its world of magic, and a riveting plot. If you've ever enjoyed an urban fantasy novel, you're certain to like this book. Brooks manages to remain accessible while writing detailed and reasonably complex prose, so If you've never tried out the genre, this is a great place to start.

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of Zoe's Tale (Old Man's War, #4): Rating - 2/5
reviews.content:
This novel is fascinating in a way. Scalzi takes events from past novels (mostly the previous book in the series) and re-frames them through a new character. Zoe's voice is strong and her characterization excellent. The same is true of her group of friends. In that it succeeds. However, having read the previous books, there is simply too much repeated here.

The narrative is fragmentary (out of necessity, because there is so much to the main plot that Zoe doesn't witness) and the only two fragments that truly add value come towards the end, significant events that only Zoe (instead of the triad of previous protagonists) witnessed. These sections shine. However, in order to make the novel stand on its own, Scalzi ends up treating us to far too much exposition, the beginning of the book is fairly weighed down with explanation and back story, mostly told to us, mostly repeating events we've already seen in previous novels with not enough extra added that they would stand on their own.

It's a shame that both the strong stories also can't stand on their own either, as this novel would have been far better as a self-contained set of shorts from Zoe's perspective. All the ingredients are there, but instead it all comes out a bit too loose to be a great novel but still too connected to be a good collection of shorts.

If you loved the series so far, go for it, otherwise it is likely not worth picking up.

reviews.content: A fun read, though a bit more heavy handed in its plotting. Scalzi's third book in the Old Man's War series is not quite as good as the novels before, but worth picking up.

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of The Hydrogen Sonata (Culture #10): Rating - 5/5
reviews.content:
It is clear that Iain Banks is one of our generations' greatest science fiction authors, a peer of Asimov for the new century, and one of last keepers of Asimov-style SF (that being both high concept and soft science). It's too bad that (failing an unlikely pop adaptation into another format like film) the soft-ish nature of the SF (mostly abandoned for hard SF, like Karl Schroeder or outright Sci-Fi Fantasy of the Star Wars variety), the extensive length of most works and the regular slower-than-average start to his narrative arcs will keep his work from gaining the mainstream acceptance it deserves.

Like all of Banks's books (especially from the Culture series) Hydrogen Sonata starts off with a bang of an inciting incident, moves sort of lazily for a while with a great deal of exposition and an initial sluggish rising action while all the plans are hatched and pieces moved into place. About 20% of the way through the novel his rising action finally catches and begins immense acceleration. Past that point it takes off at great speed, with good humor, great plotting and significant pull. Once caught in the gravity well of the primary conflict, things move excitingly apace and the book becomes difficult to put down.

That first 20% is, like most of Banks's works, the greatest obstacle, especially to a new reader because it cannot easily be skipped (like say, The Lord of the Rings' ridiculous initial world-building exercise). The exposition is necessary to entry in Banks's increasingly complex universe of the Culture, especially because it allows the reader to move through the subsequent action of the narrative without ever having to slow down. Still, it's a shame because the average reader will never make it through this portion of the novel, putting it down never to pick it up again.

Don't be that reader. The Hydrogen Sonata is yet another excellent entry in the series, perhaps in the top 3 in terms of quality, and well worth the wait.

Like all Culture novels, reading previous entries is not required but will greatly enhance the experience.
